# Accessibility Standards

## Semantic HTML
- Use proper heading hierarchy (h1-h6)
- Employ semantic elements (nav, main, section)
- Use lists for grouped content
- Add landmarks for navigation
- Include descriptive labels

## ARIA Attributes
- Add aria-labels where needed
- Use aria-expanded for toggles
- Include aria-current for navigation
- Set aria-hidden appropriately
- Maintain ARIA best practices

## Color and Contrast
- Maintain WCAG 2.1 AA standards
- Ensure sufficient text contrast
- Don't rely solely on color
- Use accessible color combinations
- Test with color blindness tools

## Interactive Elements
- Ensure keyboard navigation
- Add focus indicators
- Make clickable areas large enough
- Provide hover/focus states
- Include skip links

## Images and Media
- Add alt text for images
- Use descriptive file names
- Include image descriptions
- Provide captions where needed
- Optimize for screen readers

## Forms and Inputs
- Label all form controls
- Group related fields
- Provide clear error messages
- Include input validation
- Support keyboard interaction

## Content Structure
- Use clear headings
- Keep content scannable
- Provide consistent navigation
- Include descriptive links
- Maintain logical reading order
